Here is an example of a GUI timer component that includes editable start and stop date/time values and a boolean on/off switch:

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
import javax.swing.*;
import java.time.*;
import java.time.format.*;

public class TimerComponent extends JPanel {
    private LocalDateTime startTime, stopTime;
    private boolean on;
    private DateTimeFormatter formatter;
    private JTextField startField, stopField;
    private JToggleButton toggleButton;

    public TimerComponent() {
        formatter = DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern("yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss");

        startField = new JTextField(19);
        startField.setText(formatter.format(LocalDateTime.now()));
        startField.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
                setStartTime(LocalDateTime.parse(startField.getText(), formatter));
            }
        });

        stopField = new JTextField(19);
        stopField.setText(formatter.format(LocalDateTime.now().plusMinutes(5)));
        stopField.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
                setStopTime(LocalDateTime.parse(stopField.getText(), formatter));
            }
        });

        toggleButton = new JToggleButton("Start");
        toggleButton.addActionListener(new ActionListener() {
            public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
                toggleOnOff();
            }
        });

        setLayout(new GridLayout(2, 2));
        add(new JLabel("Start Time:"));
        add(startField);
        add(new JLabel("Stop Time:"));
        add(stopField);
        add(toggleButton);

        setStartTime(LocalDateTime.now());
        setStopTime(LocalDateTime.now().plusMinutes(5));
        toggleButton.setSelected(false);
    }

    public void setStartTime(LocalDateTime startTime) {
        this.startTime = startTime;
        startField.setText(formatter.format(startTime));
    }

    public void setStopTime(LocalDateTime stopTime) {
        this.stopTime = stopTime;
        stopField.setText(formatter.format(stopTime));
    }

    public void toggleOnOff() {
        on = !on;
        if (on) {
            toggleButton.setText("Stop");
            System.out.println("Timer started");
        } else {
            toggleButton.setText("Start");
            System.out.println("Timer stopped");
        }
    }
}
```

To use this timer component in a Swing application, you can add it to a JFrame like this:

```java
import javax.swing.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        JFrame frame = new JFrame("Timer Component");
        frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        frame.setSize(400, 200);
        frame.add(new TimerComponent());
        frame.setVisible(true);
    }
}
```

This will create a window with the timer component displayed, allowing the user to edit the start and stop time values and toggle the on/off switch to start and stop the timer.

Here is an example of Java code that uses ThreadPool to draw fractals on Swing GUI:

```java
import java.awt.Color;
import java.awt.Dimension;
import java.awt.Graphics;
import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;
import javax.swing.JFrame;
import javax.swing.JPanel;

public class FractalViewer extends JPanel {
    private static final int WIDTH = 800;
    private static final int HEIGHT = 800;
    private static final int MAX_ITERATIONS = 1000;
    private static final double ZOOM = 150;

    private ExecutorService threadPool;

    public FractalViewer() {
        int cores = Runtime.getRuntime().availableProcessors();
        threadPool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(cores);

        setPreferredSize(new Dimension(WIDTH, HEIGHT));
    }

    @Override
    public void paintComponent(Graphics g) {
        super.paintComponent(g);
        for (int x = 0; x < WIDTH; x++) {
            for (int y = 0; y < HEIGHT; y++) {
                threadPool.execute(new FractalWorker(x, y, g));
            }
        }
        threadPool.shutdown();
    }

    private class FractalWorker implements Runnable {
        private int x, y;
        private Graphics g;

        public FractalWorker(int x, int y, Graphics g) {
            this.x = x;
            this.y = y;
            this.g = g;
        }

        @Override
        public void run() {
            int iterations = 0;
            double zx, zy, cX, cY;
            zx = zy = 0;
            cX = (x - WIDTH / 2) / ZOOM;
            cY = (y - HEIGHT / 2) / ZOOM;
            while (zx * zx + zy * zy < 4 && iterations < MAX_ITERATIONS) {
                double tmp = zx * zx - zy * zy + cX;
                zy = 2.0 * zx * zy + cY;
                zx = tmp;
                iterations++;
            }
            if (iterations < MAX_ITERATIONS) {
                g.setColor(Color.BLACK);
                g.drawRect(x, y, 1, 1);
            } else {
                g.setColor(Color.WHITE);
                g.drawRect(x, y, 1, 1);
            }
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        JFrame frame = new JFrame("Fractal Viewer");
        frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        frame.add(new FractalViewer());
        frame.pack();
        frame.setLocationRelativeTo(null);
        frame.setVisible(true);
    }
}
```

This code creates a JPanel that is added to a JFrame to display the fractals. The `paintComponent` method loops through every pixel in the panel and creates a new `FractalWorker` for each one, which is executed in the thread pool. The `FractalWorker` calculates the number of iterations required to determine if a pixel is inside or outside the fractal, and sets the color of the pixel accordingly.

The number of threads in the thread pool is determined by the number of available cores on the machine, which can be obtained using the `Runtime.getRuntime().availableProcessors()` method.

To run this program, simply create a new instance of the `FractalViewer` class and add it to a JFrame, like in the `main` method shown above. When the program is run, the fractals will be rendered on the JPanel and updated in real-time as the thread pool completes the fractal calculations.

In order to calculate a matrix multiplication on an AMD GPU, you can use the OpenCL framework. Here is an example code that uses the JOCL library to perform matrix multiplication on an AMD GPU:

```java
import org.jocl.*;

public class MatrixMultiplication
{
    public static void main(String args[])
    {
        // Create the input matrices
        int N = 1024;
        float A[] = new float[N*N];
        float B[] = new float[N*N];
        float C[] = new float[N*N];
        for (int i=0; i<N; i++)
        {
            for (int j=0; j<N; j++)
            {
                A[i*N + j] = (float)i+j;
                B[i*N + j] = (float)i-j;
            }
        }

        // Initialize the OpenCL environment
        CL.setExceptionsEnabled(true);
        CLPlatform platform = CLPlatform.getPlatforms()[0];
        CLDevice device = platform.getDevices(CLDevice.Type.GPU)[0];
        CLContext context = CLContext.create(device);
        CLCommandQueue queue = device.createCommandQueue();

        // Create the input and output CLBuffers
        cl_mem A_mem = CL.clCreateBuffer(context, CL.CL_MEM_READ_ONLY | CL.CL_MEM_COPY_HOST_PTR, Sizeof.cl_float * N*N, Pointer.to(A), null);
        cl_mem B_mem = CL.clCreateBuffer(context, CL.CL_MEM_READ_ONLY | CL.CL_MEM_COPY_HOST_PTR, Sizeof.cl_float * N*N, Pointer.to(B), null);
        cl_mem C_mem = CL.clCreateBuffer(context, CL.CL_MEM_READ_WRITE, Sizeof.cl_float * N*N, null, null);

        // Create and build the OpenCL program
        String source =
            "__kernel void matrixMultiplication(__global const float *A, __global const float *B, __global float *C, const int N)\n" +
            "{\n" +
            "    int i = get_global_id(0);\n" +
            "    int j = get_global_id(1);\n" +
            "    float sum = 0.0f;\n" +
            "    for (int k=0; k<N; k++)\n" +
            "    {\n" +
            "        sum += A[i*N + k] * B[k*N + j];\n" +
            "    }\n" +
            "    C[i*N + j] = sum;\n" +
            "}";
        CLProgram program = context.createProgram(source);
        program.build();
        CLKernel kernel = program.createKernel("matrixMultiplication");

        // Set the kernel arguments
        kernel.setArg(0, A_mem);
        kernel.setArg(1, B_mem);
        kernel.setArg(2, C_mem);
        kernel.setArg(3, N);

        // Enqueue the kernel for execution
        long globalWorkSize[] = new long[] {N, N};
        long localWorkSize[] = new long[] {16, 16};
        cl_event event = new cl_event();
        CL.clEnqueueNDRangeKernel(queue, kernel, 2, null, globalWorkSize, localWorkSize, 0, null, event);

        // Wait for the kernel to complete and read the output
        CL.clWaitForEvents(1, new cl_event[] {event});
        CL.clEnqueueReadBuffer(queue, C_mem, CL.CL_TRUE, 0, Sizeof.cl_float * N*N, Pointer.to(C), 0, null, null);

        // Release the OpenCL resources
        CL.clReleaseMemObject(A_mem);
        CL.clReleaseMemObject(B_mem);
        CL.clReleaseMemObject(C_mem);
        CL.clReleaseKernel(kernel);
        CL.clReleaseProgram(program);
        CL.clReleaseCommandQueue(queue);
        CL.clReleaseContext(context);
    }
}
```

This code initializes the two input matrices `A` and `B` and creates an output matrix `C`. It then initializes the OpenCL environment, creates input and output CLBuffers, compiles an OpenCL kernel for matrix multiplication, sets the kernel arguments, enqueues the kernel for execution on the GPU, and waits for the kernel to complete and read the output. Finally, it releases the OpenCL resources.

Note that this code assumes that you have already installed the necessary AMD OpenCL drivers and JOCL library on your system. Also, you may need to adjust the `localWorkSize` parameter to match the configuration of your specific AMD GPU.
